    <description>Shrubs or small trees, sparingly to densely branched, 0.5–1.8 m, usually bearing
        similar, commonly spineless terminal branchlets arranged at right angles along major axes.
        Stem segments usually alternate, gray-green or purplish, 2–8 × 0.3–0.5 cm; tubercles linear,
        drying as elongate, riblike wrinkles, 1.1–2(–3) cm; areoles broadly elliptic, (1–)1.5–3.5 ×
        0.7–2 mm; wool white to yellow, aging gray. Spines 0–1(–3) per areole, usually in apical
        areoles to well distributed, erect, flexible, straight or arching upward or downward,
        red-brown with gray to whitish coat, tips yellow, aging red-brown, terete, angular-flattened
        basally, the longest (4–)14–45 mm; sheaths gray to purple-gray with yellow to red-brown tips
        or yellow throughout. Glochids in adaxial tuft or crescent to encircling areole, yellow or
        reddish brown, 1–3(–5) mm. Flowers: inner tepals pale yellow to greenish yellow, sometimes
        tipped red, narrowly obovate, 5–8 mm, acute, apiculate; filaments greenish yellow; anthers
        yellow; style yellow; stigma lobes greenish yellow. Fruits occasionally proliferating,
        yellow to scarlet (rarely green, sometimes tinged purple, becoming yellow), sometimes
        stipitate, obovoid, 9–15(–27) × 6–7(–12) mm, fleshy, smooth, spineless; umbilicus 2–4 mm
        deep; areoles 16–20. Seeds pale yellow, suborbicular to squarish and crenate in outline,
        warped, 3–4.5 mm diam., sides smooth, each with 1–3 large depressions; girdle smooth or with
        very narrow ridge. 2n = 22, 33, 44.</description>
